This species is known only from Parque Nacional Carara, in Puntarenas, Costa Rica, between 20 and 100 m elevation (Fig. 
2
).

This species is similar to 

Bignonia uleana

, a species from Bolivia, central western Brazil and Peru. 

Bignonia cararensis

can be recognized by the absence of interpetiolar ridges (vs. present in 

Bignonia uleana

), the inflorescences in lateral compound dichasia (vs. lateral simple dichasia in 

Bignonia uleana

), and the fruit up to 14 cm and with cylindrical delicate spines (vs. longer than 16 cm with triangular rough spines in 

Bignonia uleana

) (Table 
1
).
